name: iMIS SDK
description: Collection of REST calls to perform the different operations on the iMIS SDK Site.

folders.name: Authentication
folders.description: Tokens are issued to clients by iMIS. The client uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the iMIS server.

folders.name: Cart
folders.description: The shopping cart allows users to pay for products, memberships, event registrations, and to make donations. iMIS uses a combination of several content items on a single content record to create the cart

folders.name: Commerce
folders.description: Commerce relates to products for an online store, payments for membership dues, and financial aspects including invoices, payments, taxes, financial entities, financial accounts, and much more.

folders.name: Communications
folders.description: Communications relates to marketing campaigns, appeals, and solicitations.

folders.name: Core
folders.description: Transaction records are created for the various financial actions, such as membership joins, membership renewals, product purchases, event registrations, open invoice payments, and donations, that take place on your website. iMIS automatically groups these transactions in batches by date.

folders.name: Events
folders.description: Event creation consists of functions (program items) and registration options.

folders.name: IQA
folders.description: The Intelligent Query Architect (IQA) is the foundation for searches, lists, and data for reporting throughout iMIS.

responseCode.name: OK
responseCode.detail: Standard response for successful HTTP requests. The actual response will depend on the request method used. In a GET request, the response will contain an entity corresponding to the requested resource. In a POST request the response will contain an entity describing or containing the result of the action.

headers.name: access-control-allow-origin
headers.description: Specifies a URI that may access the resource. For requests without credentials, the server may specify '*' as a wildcard, thereby allowing any origin to access the resource.

headers.name: cache-control
headers.description: Tells all caching mechanisms from server to client whether they may cache this object. It is measured in seconds

headers.name: content-length
headers.description: The length of the response body in octets (8-bit bytes)

headers.name: content-type
headers.description: The mime type of this content

headers.name: date
headers.description: The date and time that the message was sent

headers.name: expires
headers.description: Gives the date/time after which the response is considered stale

headers.name: pragma
headers.description: Implementation-specific headers that may have various effects anywhere along the request-response chain.

headers.name: x-powered-by
headers.description: Specifies the technology (ASP.NET, PHP, JBoss, e.g.) supporting the web application (version details are often in X-Runtime, X-Version, or X-AspNet-Version)

requests.rawModeData:
{
    "$type": "Asi.Soa.Membership.DataContracts.PartyNoteData, Asi.Contracts",
    "PartyId": "18043",
    "Purpose": "Note 2",
    "Text": "DRIVING:

From the airport, take I 94 to downtown Chicago.  

Exit on Washington Street and go left at the top of the ramp, which will send you eastbound.

Follow Washington to Michigan Avenue.  

PARKING:

As you are in the very heart of Chicago, parking is not convenient.  The closest parking is just north of the Opus offices.  On Michigan Avenue, continue north past the entrance to 333, and turn right on Wacker Drive.  Just around the corner is an entrance to a public parking garage.  The valet will take your car, and you can enter the revolving doors on your right to get directly into the lobby of the 333 building.

TRAIN:

From the airport, if you do not have much luggage, public transportation is a very good option.  It is only $1.50 to take the public train from the airport to downtown.  This compares very well with the estimated $35 cab fare, and is usually faster, especially when traffic is heavy.  Find the CTA station, following signs from the baggage claim area.  The station is actually located below the parking garage.  

You will be riding the Blue Line.  Remember this for your return trip.  

Get off the train at Randolph Street.  When you exit you will find yourself on the street beneath the elevated train line.  Grab a cab ($3-4), or walk east towards State Street.  It is about 5 blocks to Michigan Avenue.  When you get there, cross Michigan and turn left, walking about 2 more blocks to the entrance of 333 N. Michigan. "
}
